[CLAIM]
The claim was tested using mixed-effects regression with regressors for the i nfluence of trial type (task switch versus task repeat), reward l evel, experimental block, and Need for Cognition scores upon l og transformed reaction times i n the task-switching paradigm. This yielded a significant three-way i nteraction, Trial type × reward × NFC, estimate = 0.0382, se= 0.0145, p = 0.008

[HYPOTHESIS]
The study predicts a three-way interaction of trial-type, reward amount, and Need for Cognition, such that larger rewards increase performance on task-switch trials relative to task-repeat trials for low-NFC i ndividuals, but this effect does not occur for high-NFC individuals.
